                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 125.8273/38b.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Brazilian Minister at Mexico City</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-05-04">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 4, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Press reports from Vera Cruz state that John B. Silliman, American Consul at San
                    Luis Potosi, has been imprisoned by General Maas <pb facs="0777" n="661"
                        xml:id="pg_661"/> for eleven days and is nightly threatened with execution.
                    Mr. Silliman is not Consul at Potosi but is Vice Consul at Saltillo and it is
                    not clear therefore whether the reports refer to Mr. Silliman at Saltillo or to
                    Mr. Bonney, Consul at Potosí. Will you please endeavor to obtain information in
                    regard to the safety of both officers and request the Foreign Office to take
                    prompt steps for their protection and for their release in case the report of
                    imprisonment is true.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bryan</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
